04311nam a22006375i 9780271076263DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20211998pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710762637 a10.1515/97802710762632doi  a(DE-B1597)583991  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aB1499.R4bW55 1999 7aPHI0160002bisacsh04a149/.72211 aWilliams, Christopher, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Cultivated Reason :bAn Essay on Hume and Humeanism /cChristopher Williams. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©1998  a1 online resource (204 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- t1. Rationalism -- t2. Bodies and Disembodiment -- t3. The Sceptic's Version -- t4. Irrationalism -- t5. Persons and Artworks -- tRetrospect -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs Plato's tripartite division of the soul, Descartes's criterion of clear and distinct ideas, and Kant's notion of the categorical imperative attest, philosophy has traditionally been wedded to rationalism and its "intellectualist" view of persons. In this book Christopher Williams seeks to wean his fellow philosophers away from an overly rationalistic self-understanding by using resources that are available within the philosophical tradition itself, including some that anticipate strands of Nietzsche's thought.The book begins by developing Hume's critique of rationalism, with reference especially to the section of the Treatise that deals with the continuing existence of bodies (an argument that subverts intellectualist criteria by attempting to satisfy them) and to his neglected essay "The Sceptic" where Hume reveals the importance of our embodiment through a comic portrayal of philosophers' efforts to "correct our sentiments." Then it moves on to ward off charges of irrationalism by showing that, although our powers of self-correction are more limited than the rationalist thinks they are, a Humean position is able both to sustain a commitment to reflection and to sensitize us to a version of irrationalism, manifest in monotheistic theologies, that is otherwise difficult to detect. The book concludes, more speculatively, with a comparison of persons to artworks in order to show how our aesthetic dimension is the source of some of the normative work previously assigned to rationalist reason.Ranging as it does across subfields from epistemology and history of philosophy to ethics and aesthetics, A Cultivated Reason should appeal to a wide audience of philosophers and to scholars in other fields as well.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aRationalism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271076263zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271076263423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271076263.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK